Essentially you always let a wave carry you, fight the instinct to kick out and paddle against it, relax and even go with it a little bit.  You let the resistance of the water to slow you down relative to the wave, until the force of the turbulence passes you enough that paddling will have an effect, then time it right and you're back, often faster than if you fought it because that usually just makes the tumble worse.  It's not just conservation of energy, kicking and paddling in turbulence is a good way to pull a muscle (not sure if that last bit would apply to a fly, resistance being different in air) but the rest certainly would explain it's use as a natural reflex in flight.
